ğŸŸ£ 2. REAL-TIME COMPANY SCENARIOS + COMMANDS + SOLUTIONS
ğŸ§µ Scenario 1: Server is slow, CPU usage is 100%
Check which process is consuming CPU:
top -o %CPU

Identify culprit:
ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head

Solution:

Kill or restart the process:

kill -9 <pid>


Or restart service:

systemctl restart tomcat

ğŸ§µ Scenario 2: Memory leak issue
Check memory usage:
free -h

List processes using high memory:
ps aux --sort=-%mem | head

Check which app is leaking:
top -o %MEM


ğŸ‘‰ Fix: Restart the service, investigate logs.

ğŸ§µ Scenario 3: Disk I/O high due to a heavy process
Find I/O heavy processes:
iotop


or:

ps aux --sort=-%io

Solution:

Throttle or stop the process.

ğŸ§µ Scenario 4: Zombie processes found
Find zombie processes:
ps aux | grep Z

Solution:

Restart parent process:

systemctl restart <service>

ğŸ§µ Scenario 5: Web server down (httpd/nginx)
Check if process is running:
systemctl status httpd

Start service:
sudo systemctl start httpd

Check port:
ss -tulnp | grep :80

ğŸ§µ Scenario 6: High load average but CPU is idle
Check load:
uptime

Check disk I/O bottleneck:
iostat -x 2


Fix: Disk performance tuning, stop heavy cron job.

ğŸ”´ 3. COMMON ISSUES + SOLUTIONS (with commands)
â— Issue 1: Process stuck in uninterruptible sleep (D)

Cause: Disk I/O, NFS hang, slow storage.

Solution:

Restart the service or unmount the stuck filesystem:

umount -f /mnt/nfs

â— Issue 2: Process won't die even after kill -9

Cause: Kernel wait state.

Solution:
Fix storage / disk/NFS issue.

â— Issue 3: Service failing on boot

Check logs:

